<div id="review_2745241204" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2745241204" />
    <a title="Eric Naykalyk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/54950739-eric-naykalyk"><img alt="Eric Naykalyk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1460724525p2/54950739.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2745241204?book_show_action=true">Mar 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric Naykalyk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric Naykalyk" href="/user/show/54950739-eric-naykalyk">Eric Naykalyk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/22718877-a-manual-for-creating-atheists">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2745241204" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4702301792957192100"><strong>A Definitive Disappointment</strong><br/><br/>As a conservative Christian, I enjoy seeking out resources from those with whom I disagree. I was originally excited to read this book as an opportunity for opposition research, as it were. Unfortunately, this book was a tremendous disappointment. As is typical of modern day atheist literature, this book is strong in rhetoric, and weak in actual content. Riddled with logical fallacies and a general lack of proper philosophical distinctions, this book attacks popular pr</span>
  <span id="freeText4702301792957192100" style="display:none"><strong>A Definitive Disappointment</strong><br /><br />As a conservative Christian, I enjoy seeking out resources from those with whom I disagree. I was originally excited to read this book as an opportunity for opposition research, as it were. Unfortunately, this book was a tremendous disappointment. As is typical of modern day atheist literature, this book is strong in rhetoric, and weak in actual content. Riddled with logical fallacies and a general lack of proper philosophical distinctions, this book attacks popular presentations of religion and completely ignores the best apologetic arguments that exists. Furthermore, this book ignores historical atheistic philosophy, such as the work of Nietzsche and Sartre. I would advise Professor Boghossian, who does seem intelligent in his own right, to stop shooting in a fish barrel and engage with the works of Van Till and Bahnsen.<br />If you want the best of rhetorical argumentation for atheism, ignore this book and pick up Hitchens. If you want substantive atheistic philosophy, read virtually anything prior to 1940. I'll still take the intellectual honesty of Neitzsche over modern day atheism any day of the week.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4702301792957192100" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

