  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1082211922" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1082211922" />
    <a title="Collin Duncan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21379448-collin-duncan"><img alt="Collin Duncan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1371441543p2/21379448.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1082211922?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Collin Duncan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Collin Duncan" href="/user/show/21379448-collin-duncan">Collin Duncan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1082211922" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10453392074787376295">With a chapter left to go in the book, here&apos;s the deal: I actually liked it. I thought it was simple, fast paced, and I honestly can&apos;t say I&apos;ve ever read a book that was so well cited. This is not a large book by any means, but probably half of it was citations and sources. Remarkable. The arguments are valid and hard hitting and the author writes with cutting humor. So why only two stars?<br/><br/>Ultimately, the book was ruined by two things for me: first, the premise itself. I feel this author&apos;s wit an</span>
  <span id="freeText10453392074787376295" style="display:none">With a chapter left to go in the book, here's the deal: I actually liked it. I thought it was simple, fast paced, and I honestly can't say I've ever read a book that was so well cited. This is not a large book by any means, but probably half of it was citations and sources. Remarkable. The arguments are valid and hard hitting and the author writes with cutting humor. So why only two stars?<br /><br />Ultimately, the book was ruined by two things for me: first, the premise itself. I feel this author's wit and knowledge (and unbelievable research skills) would be better suited elsewhere rather than trying to turn atheism into little more than a religion. Despite Dawkins' glowing report of this book, nothing else about it really embodies what freethinkers have been thinking for years. In fact, it probably hurts atheism overall. Many of the practical aspects of evangelical religions that atheists dispute (such as aggressive conversion tactics) are embodied here in these very pages! Atheism is not a religion! In my opinion, would it be nice if everyone suddenly became an atheist and religion dissipated? Yes, but that's just my opinion. I wouldn't want anyone to commit intellectual suicide in the process and simply take my word for it because I foisted it upon them. I would rather people conclude it for themselves. Of course, this is why there are relatively few atheists, but you know what they say about quantity versus quality...<br /><br />Second, the author misunderstands religion greatly and boils it down in ways that no religious person I've ever met or read would ever do. His tactics target only the most base and intellectually devoid believers yet this demographic is also the one least likely to convert no matter what. While amusing, his understanding of faith is small: He doesn't seem to get how to someone on the "inside" of a religion, faith makes perfect sense and dismantling that is next to impossible due to the very nature of accepting things without question. Logical arguments hailed from the street corner will not bring the faithful to tears weeping at the feet of reason. <br /><br />While reading this I enjoyed myself, but that was about it. There's nothing here particularly groundbreaking and nothing practical at all. Atheists should not seek converts. That's not the point. Look elsewhere for your fill of intellectualism and leave this book next to the proverbial (or literal) toilet. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10453392074787376295" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


